### Reusable Code Snippets:

#### 1. Singleton Pattern for Asset Management
The `Assets` class follows a singleton design pattern to ensure only one instance manages all assets throughout the application lifecycle.
```cpp
static Assets& GetInstance() {
    static Assets instance;
    return instance;
}
```

#### 2. Partition Initialization in Constructor
The constructor calls `InitializePartition()` to set up the storage partition during object construction.
```cpp
Assets::Assets() {
    partition_valid_ = InitializePartition();
}
```

#### 3. Memory Mapping Cleanup in Destructor
Proper cleanup of memory-mapped partitions is handled in the destructor using `esp_partition_munmap`.
```cpp
Assets::~Assets() {
    if (mmap_handle_ != 0) {
        esp_partition_munmap(mmap_handle_);
    }
}
```

#### 4. Asset Data Retrieval with Validation
Retrieves asset data by validating magic bytes and calculating correct pointer offsets.
```cpp
bool Assets::GetAssetData(const std::string& name, void*& ptr, size_t& size) {
    auto asset = assets_.find(name);
    if (asset == assets_.end()) {
        return false;
    }
    auto data = (const char*)(mmap_root_ + asset->second.offset);
    if (data[0] != 'Z' || data[1] != 'Z') {
        ESP_LOGE(TAG, "The asset %s is not valid with magic %02x%02x", name.c_str(), data[0], data[1]);
        return false;
    }

    ptr = static_cast<void*>(const_cast<char*>(data + 2));
    size = asset->second.size;
    return true;
}
```

#### 5. Private Member Variables for State Tracking
Use of member variables to track partition validity, checksum status, and mapped memory root.
```cpp
const esp_partition_t* partition_ = nullptr;
esp_partition_mmap_handle_t mmap_handle_ = 0;
const char* mmap_root_ = nullptr;
bool partition_valid_ = false;
bool checksum_valid_ = false;
std::map<std::string, Asset> assets_;
```

